We change our posture in the world from
passive consumers of technology

234
00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:10.000
to become active creators of technology.

235
00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:15.000
We build the infrastructure that we
control, safeguard and own.

236
00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:19.000
We keep our nation's digital destiny
family in our own hands.

237
00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:24.000
And this is what digital sovereignty means
in practice, not to be in isolation,

238
00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:29.000
but ownership, not dependence, but
partnership in our own terms.

239
00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:33.000
Distinguished participants, the United
Republic of Tanzania,

240
00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.000
does not speak of this in theory.

241
00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:40.000
We are leaving the practice, built on the
three pillars of progress.

242
00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:43.000
First, it's the right League of
Foundations.

243
00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:47.000
Under the E-Government Authority Act of
2020 for Tanzania,

244
00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:49.000
we changed the rules of the game.

245
00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:53.000
We empowered our public institutions to
move away

246
00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:58.000
from fragmented, costly proprietary
licenses and to build instead

247
00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:04.000
on flexible, open source software that are
running on shared national infrastructure.

248
00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:10.000
It is for this reason that today more than
90% of our government systems

249
00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:14.000
are built on open source technologies and
all around them,

250
00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:19.000
laws such as the personal data protection
out of 2023,

251
00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:25.000
the Cyber Crimes Act and our own
electronic and postal communications law

252
00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:30.000
allow us to safeguard citizens' privacy,
secure our services,

253
00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:34.000
and exchange data seamlessly across the
government,

254
00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:39.000
through open interfaces and connected
services that are full in-house.

255
00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:42.000
Second, it is the clear institutional
leadership.

256
00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:47.000
Through our E-Government Authority, we
created a single point of coordination,

257
00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:49.655
one body to set the standards and

258
00:20:49.655 --> 00:20:54.000
to enforce technical compliance across the
government.

259
00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:56.000
The result is discipline.

260
00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:02.000
Every new system must contribute and draw
from our shared public infrastructure.

261
00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:05.000
Our data is never locked away,

262
00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:10.000
and even a shtazanian shielding of digital
investment is built to last,

263
00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:14.000
but also to be enhanced, not discarded and
replaced.

264
00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:16.000
Third, it is an empowered workforce.

265
00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:19.000
We took the funds once spent on external
vendors

266
00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:23.000
and expensive licenses and invested them
in our own people.

267
00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:26.000
We've done capacity building for 500
public officials

268
00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:31.000
that have been trained as a collaborative
or community of internal developers,

269
00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:34.000
citizens building for citizens,

270
00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:37.000
owning the very systems that they create.

271
00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:41.000
Excellencies, Tanzania's experience proves
a simple truth.

272
00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:45.000
With the right laws, with the clear
leadership,

273
00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:50.000
and an empowered workforce, building an
independent digital infrastructure,

274
00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:54.000
it is not the privilege of a wealthy few,

275
00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:59.000
but it is within reach of every nation
that is willing to choose it.

276
00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:06.000
And this is precisely why open-source
program offices for good matter so deeply.

277
00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:09.000
Ospots turn good intentions into lasting
institutions.

278
00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:15.000
They are how government share what works,
reuse what others have built,

279
00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:19.000
and give back to global commons for
digital public goods.

280
00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:24.000
They are how the open-source promises of
the global digital compact

281
00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:28.000
that are becoming real for ordinary people
in a clinic,

282
00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:32.000
be it in a classroom, be it in a tax
office.

283
00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:38.000
And they are how South-South Corporation
moves from words to working code.

284
00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:43.000
What we have built in Daris Alam can serve
King Shasa,

285
00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:49.000
can serve Nairobi, can serve Kingston, can
serve Rabaa and other places.

286
00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:53.000
When we open our solutions, we multiply
them.

287
00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:57.000
So it is my call to every leader, to every
innovator,

288
00:22:57.000 --> 00:23:00.000
but also every partner present here today.

289
00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:02.000
Let us sustain the momentum.

290
00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:07.000
Let us break down the silos between our
institutions and organizations and countries,

291
00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:09.000
and across our borders.

292
00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:14.000
Let us build adaptable, transparent
systems that put our citizens,

293
00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:17.000
not our vendors at the very centre.

294
00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:21.000
Open-source has ended as the key to our
own innovation.

295
00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:27.000
Let us use them together to secure a
digitally sovereign, inclusive,

296
00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:30.000
and a prosperous future for all
organizations.

