She's the Executive Director of the Apache
Software Foundation.

466
00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:27.000
Karen Sandler is in the room today.

467
00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:30.000
She is the Executive Director of the
Software Freedom Conservancy.

468
00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:32.381
And I could take my entire time to keep
going here

469
00:37:32.381 --> 00:37:34.000
but I just wanted to mention a few

470
00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:38.000
and remind everyone that the Linux
Foundation is one part of this community,

471
00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:42.000
and we're very grateful to be a part of
that community.

472
00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:45.163
Today,I thought I would talk about

473
00:37:45.163 --> 00:37:50.000
how open-source is impacting artificial
intelligence

474
00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:55.000
and how artificial intelligence is
conversely impacting open-source,

475
00:37:55.000 --> 00:37:58.125
so thatyou can all get an idea of the
opportunities and

476
00:37:58.125 --> 00:38:00.000
the challenges around open-source

477
00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:06.000
as it relates to AI. There's a famous movie
in the United States that has a saying,

478
00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:11.000
"Sometimes you eat the bear, and sometimes
the bear eats you.

479
00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:14.000
Sometimes you win, sometimes you get
challenges."

480
00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:19.000
The good news in artificial intelligence
as it relates to open-source,

481
00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:24.000
if you think of the layers of technology
that are required to deploy AI

482
00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:32.000
from a GPU and a data center to the software
that is used to run that data center,

483
00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:36.000
to the software that is used to train
models, to the models themselves,

484
00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:39.000
to the agent frameworks on top of that.

485
00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:45.000
Just above the hardware, open-source is
the entire stack.

486
00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:49.048
Every layer,at the operating system
layer,Linux,at the inference and

487
00:38:49.048 --> 00:38:50.000
deployment layer

488
00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:55.000
Kubernetes, at the training layer,
PyTorch, at the agentic layer,

489
00:38:55.000 --> 00:38:58.000
open frameworks like MCP and much, much
more.

490
00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:03.000
Top to bottom, the entire stack is built
on open-source,

491
00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:08.000
and that's critical for any organization
or government that wants to leverage

492
00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:10.000
artificial intelligence.

493
00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:16.000
Even in open-weight models, open-source is
very, very close,

494
00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:21.000
and these days, three to six months behind
frontier models.

495
00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:26.000
I think we're going to see this year,
people start paying much more attention

496
00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:30.000
to open models, not just because they're
very, very good,

497
00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:33.000
but because they're very cost-effective.

498
00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:36.000
The Linux Foundation and Harvard did a
study last year

499
00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:42.000
on the costs of open models versus
proprietary API consumption,

500
00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:50.000
and we found that roughly $50 billion a
year is overspent on models

501
00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:55.000
that could have -- on work that could have
been done using open-weight models,

502
00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:59.000
and I think we're going to see even more
transition to open models

503
00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:02.000
as people start to realize the economic
value of that.

504
00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:07.000
So I think that we are doing well in
open-source

505
00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:10.000
as a fundamental building block of
artificial intelligence,

506
00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:14.000
where we're having some challenges is in a
couple of areas.

507
00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:21.000
One, in data. Unfortunately, we are seeing
the world go from an Internet,

508
00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:23.000
which was very open and shared a lot of
data,

509
00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:27.000
to unfortunately a world where data is
getting a little more closed

510
00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:29.000
and a little more scarce.

511
00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:33.000
Now you have tools from organizations that
can block crawlers

512
00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:37.000
to get access to what had been
traditionally open data.

513
00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:42.000
We're seeing the licensing and sort of
hoarding the large-scale data initiatives,

514
00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:48.000
and I'm hoping that the Linux Foundation
and other organizations like us

515
00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:54.000
can help in a counterweight to that
building open consortiums of shared data.

516
00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:57.000
For example, we have our Overture Maps
project,

517
00:40:57.000 --> 00:41:02.000
which is the largest shared geospatial
mapping data infrastructure in the world.

518
00:41:02.000 --> 00:41:08.000
For every action, there's a reaction, and
as we see more closed data,

519
00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:11.000
I'm hoping we'll see a reaction just like
we saw in proprietary software

520
00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:16.000
to open source from closed data to
intentional open data sharing.

521
00:41:16.000 --> 00:41:21.000
Governments around the world can be a big
part of that effort.

522
00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:24.000
So I think that's one of the big
challenges in AI

523
00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:27.000
as it relates to the concept of openness.

524
00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:31.897
But I want to spend a few of my final
moments on the most immediate and

525
00:41:31.897 --> 00:41:33.000
urgent challenge

526
00:41:33.000 --> 00:41:37.000
that artificial intelligence poses to open
source.

527
00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:40.000
And that is in the area of cybersecurity.

528
00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:46.000
Today, the mean time to exploit for a
vulnerability in software,

529
00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:49.000
proprietary -- oh, or open source, this
isn't just about open source,

530
00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:52.000
is now negative seven days.

531
00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:58.000
If maybe in 2018, 2020, that time was 60
days.

532
00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:04.000
The speed at which a vulnerability can be
discovered and exploited now is faster

533
00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:10.000
than we can keep up with in terms of our
ability to patch.

534
00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:12.169
And sowhen you think aboutthis

535
00:42:12.169 --> 00:42:16.000
when you look at these artificial
intelligence models

536
00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:23.000
the good harness being used by attackers
to exploit vulnerabilities in software,

537
00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:27.000
that is an immediate urgent daunting
problem.

538
00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:29.143
The good news is,the defenders

539
00:42:29.143 --> 00:42:33.000
in this case the deus spore of open source
maintainers

540
00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:39.000
have access to the same technology to
defend the stack.

541
00:42:39.000 --> 00:42:46.000
And this is something that I think
requires nothing more than willpower.

542
00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:52.000
Setting aside all of our collective
competitive differences in the corporate world

543
00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:55.000
are differences in the open source world.

544
00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:59.000
And let me tell you, there are a lot of
differences of opinion in open source.

545
00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:10.000
And exercising the will to come together
and retire 20 plus years of technical debt

546
00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:18.000
by building a group of organizations and
maintainers that can use this AI technology

547
00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:20.952
to scan,to find vulnerabilities

548
00:43:20.952 --> 00:43:26.000
but most importantly come to the most
critical people

549
00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:32.337
the open source maintainers,to provide
them working code thatthey can merge into

550
00:43:32.337 --> 00:43:34.000
their software easily

551
00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:36.214
without extra burden on them so

552
00:43:36.214 --> 00:43:41.000
that we can collectively secure the corpus
of open source software.

553
00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:43.759
And the final thought I'll leave you
withis when

554
00:43:43.759 --> 00:43:46.000
Jim says corpus of open source software

555
00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:52.000
what does that mean? It means roughly a
million open source projects.

556
00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:55.070
These are not the 80 million repos on
GitHub

557
00:43:55.070 --> 00:43:58.000
these are the million open source projects

558
00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:00.789
starting fromLinux andthen long tail
dependencies and

559
00:44:00.789 --> 00:44:03.000
kind of every software component out there

560
00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:08.000
that are used in production systems and
critical infrastructure, banking systems,

561
00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:13.000
telecommunications, utilities, the energy
sector, government systems.

562
00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:17.220
It's a million different discrete
components and

563
00:44:17.220 --> 00:44:21.000
we need to look at every single one of
them

564
00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:23.471
leverage this intelligence and

565
00:44:23.471 --> 00:44:28.000
spend the next six to 12 months hardening
this software

566
00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:33.000
getting it secure, leveraging this
technology to make that happen.

567
00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:39.968
And if we can exercise thatwill,we will
restore the equilibrium between attackers

568
00:44:39.968 --> 00:44:41.000
anddefenders

569
00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:43.000
in the cybersecurity world.

570
00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:47.000
Most importantly, and this is for the open
source community to understand the most,

571
00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:52.000
a lot of us have been working in here for
20 plus years, some 30, 40.

572
00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:59.000
It took us this long to create open source
as a trusted resource.

573
00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:03.833
That trust can be broken if we do not meet
this moment and

574
00:45:03.833 --> 00:45:06.000
collectively work together

575
00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:13.000
come together to collectively secure this
large ecosystem of open source components.

576
00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:17.000
So that is, I think, the most immediate
and urgent challenge that AI presents us.

577
00:45:17.000 --> 00:45:19.000
The good news is that we have these tools.

578
00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:22.000
The good news is that the entire stack is
built on open source.

579
00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:26.000
The good news is that we can counter
closed data with open data,

580
00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:30.000
and the Linux Foundation looks forward to
working with all of our partners

581
00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:32.000
and all the governments around the world
to do just that.

582
00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:43.000
Thank you. [applause] Thank you very much,
Mr. Jim Zemling.

583
00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:47.000
Our next and last speaker before we start
our panel today will be Louise McKeever.

584
00:45:47.000 --> 00:45:48.888
She's the government CIO

585
00:45:48.888 --> 00:45:54.000
Chief Information Officer at the
Department of Public Expenditure

586
00:45:54.000 --> 00:45:57.000
Public Service Reform and Digitization of
Ireland.

587
00:45:57.000 --> 00:45:59.000
Louise, you have a floor.

588
00:45:59.000 --> 00:46:11.000
[applause] Good morning, everyone, and
distinguished guests.

589
00:46:11.000 --> 00:46:14.000
I'm absolutely delighted to be here.

590
00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:17.000
I visited New York a couple of times, but
this is my first time in the UN,

591
00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:22.000
so it's an absolute privilege to be here
and talk a little bit about open source

592
00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:25.779
and digital sovereignty in a connected
world,and thatwill be from

593
00:46:25.779 --> 00:46:27.000
an Irish perspective.

594
00:46:27.000 --> 00:46:29.000
Just give you a little background.

595
00:46:29.000 --> 00:46:34.000
I took up their oldest government CIO a
month ago, so I want to thank you all

596
00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:39.000
for coming here today and celebrating my
one-month work anniversary,

597
00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:42.000
but I'm no stranger to operating across
government.

598
00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:45.188
Previously,I worked forfive anda half
years as

599
00:46:45.188 --> 00:46:49.000
the CIO in the Department of
Agriculture,Food andMarine

600
00:46:49.000 --> 00:46:52.000
where their policy is open source first.

601
00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:57.000
So their technology stack is built on open
source, which is very much aligned

602
00:46:57.000 --> 00:47:00.368
to the systems andservices forcentral
government

603
00:47:00.368 --> 00:47:05.000
our enterprise systems are also built on
open source technologies.

604
00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:08.000
So one of my mandates is to drive digital
government,

605
00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:12.000
so the technology stack will be the
enabler to drive digital government,

606
00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:15.000
but it's not just the technology that's
going to drive,

607
00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:17.000
it's also collaboration.

608
00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:21.500
I think collaboration has been a big focus
of discussions over the last couple of

609
00:47:21.500 --> 00:47:22.000
days.

610
00:47:22.000 --> 00:47:28.000
So I'm going to start by talking or
sponsoring three questions,

611
00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:33.000
which I can get it to work now, apologies,
which is what is digital sovereignty,

612
00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:36.000
why is it becoming a priority for
governments,

613
00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:41.000
and how can open source help Ireland build
more resilient public services.

614
00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:44.488
So digital sovereignty is the ability of
an organization and

615
00:47:44.488 --> 00:47:46.000
in my situation government

616
00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:53.000
to maintain control over its digital
infrastructure, data and technologies.

617
00:47:53.000 --> 00:47:56.000
In today's environment of cross-border
data flows,

618
00:47:56.000 --> 00:47:59.000
AI advancement and geopolitical risk,

619
00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:03.000
digital sovereignty is a national security
concern.

620
00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:08.000
So digital sovereignty is about choice and
resilience.

621
00:48:08.000 --> 00:48:11.000
Why is it becoming a priority for
governments?

622
00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:13.604
While public services are increasingly
digital

623
00:48:13.604 --> 00:48:17.000
we talked a lot the last couple of days
aboutdigitalization.

624
00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:21.384
And in Ireland,to drive digitalization,we
have what's known as

625
00:48:21.384 --> 00:48:24.000
the Better Public Services 2030 plan.

626
00:48:24.000 --> 00:48:29.000
And division is for a professional,
innovative and agile public service

627
00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:35.000
that is responsive, reliable, fair, open
and trustworthy.

628
00:48:35.000 --> 00:48:40.000
These drivers of trust are central to all
reform efforts.

629
00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:45.000
The requirement of 2030 is to have 100% of
public services available online,

630
00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:50.000
and 90% of applicable services are
consumed digitally.

631
00:48:50.000 --> 00:48:53.000
Digital sovereignty is also a priority for
governments

632
00:48:53.000 --> 00:48:59.000
due to increasing focus on cyber security,
resilience and data control.

633
00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:03.000
So how can open source help Ireland build
more resilient public services?

634
00:49:03.000 --> 00:49:06.000
And we've heard a lot about the benefits
of open source,

635
00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:08.262
obviously over the last couple of days

636
00:49:08.262 --> 00:49:11.000
but just to name a few is greater
transparency

637
00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:16.000
improve interoperability, the ability to
adapt solutions to public sector needs,

638
00:49:16.000 --> 00:49:19.000
and collaboration across public service
bodies,

639
00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:24.000
which is a key driver of Ireland's digital
government agenda.

640
00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:27.000
So open source and digital sovereignty in
practice.

641
00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:30.000
So how does open source contribute to
digital sovereignty?

642
00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:36.242
Well,by increasing control,improving
resilience,supporting security and

643
00:49:36.242 --> 00:49:38.000
building capability.

644
00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:42.000
It is built through trusted technology
choices, secure architecture

645
00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:45.000
and an open approach that gives
governments and organisations

646
00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:50.000
the ability to shape, adapt and govern
their digital environments.

647
00:49:50.000 --> 00:49:53.000
From Ireland's perspective, we're at a
critical point,

648
00:49:53.000 --> 00:49:57.000
or a very important point in Ireland's
digital journey.

649
00:49:57.000 --> 00:50:00.000
Across governments, we are working to
deliver public services

650
00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:04.000
that are more connected, more consistent
and easy to use.

651
00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:09.000
Our vision is clear to provide inclusive,
high quality and integrated public services

652
00:50:09.000 --> 00:50:13.000
that meet people's needs and improve their
everyday lives.

653
00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:16.000
A whole of government approach sets out to
help departments

654
00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:19.000
address key strategic investment questions

655
00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:23.000
and choose effective scalable
technology-based solutions.

656
00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:27.000
And in particular, to help them to consider
using digital public infrastructure,

657
00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:29.000
a lot of what we spoke about yesterday,

658
00:50:29.000 --> 00:50:34.000
for economies of scale and ROI, return of
investment.

659
00:50:34.000 --> 00:50:37.000
The digital public services plan, as
mentioned, is Ireland's roadmap

660
00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:42.000
to fully digital, customer user-centric
and inclusive public services,

661
00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:48.000
aiming to meet that 100% services online
by 2030, as mentioned.

662
00:50:48.000 --> 00:50:51.000
At the core of the plan is the life events
approach,

663
00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:56.000
and I know that was mentioned yesterday,
where we reorganized services around,

664
00:50:56.000 --> 00:51:01.000
I suppose, critical or significant moments
in people's lives or citizens' lives,

665
00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:05.000
such as becoming a parent, starting
school, learning to drive,

666
00:51:05.000 --> 00:51:09.000
accessing housing and planning for
retirement.

667
00:51:09.000 --> 00:51:13.000
The plan introduces government digital
blocks to support service delivery,

668
00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:17.000
including a government digital wallet and
shared digital platforms,

669
00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:21.000
which enable collaboration across public
service bodies.

670
00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:22.524
Now,I stand to be corrected here

671
00:51:22.524 --> 00:51:25.000
but I believe Ireland is the only member
state in EU

672
00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:28.000
that is pursuing both life events as a
methodology

673
00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:32.000
and the GovStack Building Blocks
architecture, as our target architecture,

674
00:51:32.000 --> 00:51:35.000
working with partners and providers WHO
are all supporting

675
00:51:35.000 --> 00:51:38.000
our open-source development efforts.

676
00:51:38.000 --> 00:51:42.000
A key enabler of Ireland's transformation
is the government digital wallet,

677
00:51:42.000 --> 00:51:46.000
which I mentioned, and at a high level,
the wallets will give people a secure

678
00:51:46.000 --> 00:51:50.000
and convenient way to prove WHO they are
to store important documents

679
00:51:50.000 --> 00:51:53.000
and to access services more easily.

680
00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:56.000
It has the potential to simplify how
people interact with the state

681
00:51:56.000 --> 00:52:01.000
at important points in life, and it is
underpinned by strong principles,

682
00:52:01.000 --> 00:52:04.000
such as privacy, security and user
control,

683
00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:09.000
ensuring that individuals decide what
information they share and when they share it.

684
00:52:09.000 --> 00:52:13.000
For government and the wider public
service, the wallet also has many benefits.

685
00:52:13.000 --> 00:52:16.000
It can support more efficient and scalable
service delivery

686
00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:20.000
by reducing manual processing, paper-based
administration,

687
00:52:20.000 --> 00:52:23.000
repeated verification checks and
duplicated service journeys,

688
00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:26.000
and that certainly was discussed over the
last few days.

689
00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:28.000
In that sense, it's not just a new app.

690
00:52:28.000 --> 00:52:30.298
It's part of the infrastructure that

691
00:52:30.298 --> 00:52:34.000
can help public services work better
across organizations.

692
00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:38.000
We have just concluded a comprehensive
public consultation process,

693
00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:42.000
and I'm delighted to say that Ireland is
moving into a national pilot testing phase,

694
00:52:42.000 --> 00:52:47.000
over the coming days, so really exciting
times for Ireland.

695
00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:52.000
Just to summarize, I've got a couple of
key takeaways for you.

696
00:52:52.000 --> 00:52:56.000
Digital sovereignty is becoming a
strategic issue for government.

